<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>John Duns Scotus</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Thu May 31, 2001; substantive revision Mon Dec 15, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
John Duns Scotus (1263/66&ndash;1308) was one of the most important
and influential philosopher-theologians of the High Middle Ages. His
brilliantly complex and nuanced thought, which earned him the
honorific &ldquo;the Subtle Doctor,&rdquo; left a mark on discussions
of such disparate topics as the semantics of religious language, the
problem of universals, divine illumination, and the nature of human
freedom. This essay first lays out what is known about Scotus&rsquo;s
life and the dating of his works. It then offers an overview of some
of his key positions in four main areas of philosophy: natural
theology, metaphysics, the theory of knowledge, and ethics and moral
psychology.</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
<ul>
	<li><a href="#LifWor">1. Life and Works</a>

