<tr>
<td><img src="../../symbols/pp.gif" alt="phil papers icon" /></td>
<td><a href="https://philpapers.org/sep/duns-scotus/" target="other">Enhanced bibliography for this entry</a>
at <a href="https://philpapers.org/" target="other">PhilPapers</a>, with links to its database.</td>
</tr>

</table>
</blockquote>
</div>

<div id="other-internet-resources">

<h2><a id="Oth">Other Internet Resources</a></h2>

<ul>

<li>Duns Scotus,
 <a href="https://ethicascoti.com/Reportatio%20IIA%20d%206%20q%202.pdf" target="other"><em>Reportatio</em> IIA d. 6 q. 2</a>,
 translated by Thomas Williams from critical edition by Garrett
Smith.</li>

<li>Duns Scotus,
 <a href="https://www.aristotelophile.com/current.htm" target="other"><em>Ordinatio</em></a>,
 translated by Peter Simpson, CUNY/Graduate Center.</li>
 <li><a href="https://abelard.hypotheses.org/scotus-bibliography" target="other">Duns Scotus Bibliography</a>,
 from 1950 to the present. This very valuable bibliography of work on
Duns Scotus is maintained by Tobias Hoffmann.</li>
 <li><a href="http://www.franciscan-archive.org/scotus/" target="other">The Franciscan Archive: John Duns Scotus</a>.
 Offers Latin texts, translations, scholarly papers, and other
resources.</li>
 <li><a href="https://ethicascoti.com/additionaltranslations.html" target="other">The Ethics of John Duns Scotus: Additional Translations</a>.
 Offers translations of some of Scotus&rsquo;s ethical writings.</li>
</ul>
</div>

